\n\n**Key parsing entry points** (defined in Parser.h, lines 1831, 1851, and specialized in Parser.cpp):\n- `Parser::globalBody(GlobalSharedContext* globalsc)` - Parses global script bodies (line 1867 in Parser.cpp)\n- `Parser::evalBody(EvalSharedContext* evalsc)` - Parses eval script bodies (line 1777 in Parser.cpp)\n- `Parser::moduleBody(ModuleSharedContext* modulesc)` - Parses ES6 module bodies (line 1926 in Parser.cpp)\n\nThese methods return `ParseNode*` objects representing the AST.\n\n### 4. Abstract Syntax Tree (js/src/frontend/ParseNode.h and ParseNode.cpp)\nThe Parser generates an Abstract Syntax Tree composed of ParseNode objects.\n\n**Base class:**\n- `ParseNode` (line 712 in ParseNode.h) - Base class for all AST nodes\n\n**Node Types:**\nParseNode.h defines a comprehensive set of node types through the `FOR_EACH_PARSE_NODE_KIND` macro (lines 63-150), including:\n- Expression nodes: `Name`, `NumberExpr`, `StringExpr`, `CallExpr`, `NewExpr`, etc.\n- Statement nodes: `ExpressionStmt`, `IfStmt`, `WhileStmt`, `ForStmt`, `ReturnStmt`, etc.\n- Declaration nodes: `VarStmt`, `LetDecl`, `ConstDecl`, `Function`, `ImportDecl`, etc.\n- Specialized nodes: `FunctionNode`, `ModuleNode`, `LexicalScopeNode`, etc.\n\nSpecific node subtypes include:\n- `UnaryNode` - Single child node\n- `BinaryNode` - Two child nodes\n- `ListNode` - Multiple child nodes\n- `TernaryNode` - Three child nodes\n- `PropertyAccess`, `CallNode`, etc. - Specialized nodes\n\n### 5. Bytecode Emitter (js/src/frontend/BytecodeEmitter.h and BytecodeEmitter.cpp)\nThe BytecodeEmitter class converts the AST into bytecode sequences.\n\n**BytecodeEmitter:**\n- Defined as `struct MOZ_STACK_CLASS BytecodeEmitter` (line 210 in BytecodeEmitter.h)\n- Contains comprehensive bytecode generation logic\n\n**Key method:**\n- `BytecodeEmitter::emitScript(ParseNode* body)` (line 525 in BytecodeEmitter.h) - Main entry point for bytecode generation\n  - Recursively traverses the AST\n  - Emits appropriate bytecode instructions for each node type\n  - Manages the bytecode section (prologue and main parts)\n  - Generates try-catch and exception handling information\n\nThe emitter produces bytecode stored in a `BytecodeSection` object, which contains:\n- Bytecode instruction sequence (array of `jsbytecode` values)\n- Source notes for debugging\n- Exception handling information\n- GC thing indices for object literals, functions, etc.\n\n### 6. Bytecode Output - JSScript (js/src/vm/JSScript.h and JSScript.cpp)\nThe final bytecode is encapsulated in the JSScript object, which represents a compiled JavaScript function or script.\n\n**JSScript Class:**\n- Defined as `class JSScript : public js::BaseScript` (line 1787 in JSScript.h)\n- Contains the bytecode instructions and all associated metadata\n\n**Key methods for creating JSScript:**\n- `JSScript::fromStencil(JSContext* cx, ...)` (line 1826 in JSScript.h) - Creates a new JSScript from compilation stencil\n- `JSScript::fullyInitFromStencil(JSContext* cx, ...)` (line 1818 in JSScript.h) - Fully initializes JSScript with bytecode data from stencil\n- `JSScript::Create(...)` (line 1800 in JSScript.h) - Creates a JSScript instance\n\n**Bytecode Access:**\n- `JSScript::code()` (line 1844) - Returns pointer to bytecode instruction array (`jsbytecode*`)\n- `JSScript::length()` (line 1863) - Returns bytecode length in bytes\n- `JSScript::codeEnd()` (line 1868) - Returns pointer to end of bytecode\n\n## Data Flow Summary\n\n1. **Source Text Input** → `CompileGlobalScriptToStencilWithInput()` (BytecodeCompiler.h)\n2. **Tokenization & Parsing** → `Parser::globalBody()` (Parser.h/cpp) → Returns `ParseNode*` (AST root)\n3. **AST Generation** → Various `ParseNode` subtypes (ParseNode.h)\n4. **Bytecode Emission** → `BytecodeEmitter::emitScript()` (BytecodeEmitter.h/cpp) → Generates bytecode instructions\n5. **Bytecode Output** → `JSScript` (JSScript.h/cpp) → Contains compiled bytecode and metadata\n\nThis pipeline enables SpiderMonkey to compile JavaScript into efficient bytecode that can be executed by the JavaScript virtual machine or further optimized by the JIT compiler.\n"
